# <%= current_page.data.title %>

Use [infrastructure as code][] (IaC) to define, deploy and manage your infrastructure. Store your 
infrastructure code in a version control system such as Git to provide robust change tracking, 
change approval processes and auditability. 

GDS use a small selection of infrastructure as code tools because different tools are better 
suited to different tasks. 

## Puppet

The use of [Puppet][] at GDS is diminishing as we move more of our infrastructure to containers 
and higher level services.

If your environment consists of a simple deployment artefact like an [Amazon Machine Image (AMI)][], 
Puppet may not be necessary, but the process for building that artefact must still be 
codified and version controlled.

## Terraform

Teams should use [Terraform][] to configure third party cloud infrastructure like Amazon Web 
Services (AWS) or [Fastly][].

Terraform supports a [large number of providers][], and you can configure it to support multiple 
environments with different parameters. See the [govuk-aws][] repository as an example.

### When to use Terraform

Consider Terraform as the default choice for managing infrastructure as code. 

Terraform should be used when: 

* you need to manage resources for one or more third-party providers in a single codebase
* you want to leverage existing Terraform modules and community resources
* you want to benefit from an extensive library of existing terraform code within GDS
* you do not need the complex language features of a high-level programming language
* your team prefers declarative configuration over imperative programming
* you want your teams IaC to be easily maintainable by 
    * team members across GDS
    * team members who are unfamiliar with a specific programming language 

### Versioning

Due to the high rate of change in many cloud provider offerings we
recommend you keep your Terraform versions and codebases up to date. A
version manager such as [tfenv](https://github.com/tfutils/tfenv),
already used by a number of GDS teams, can help you with supporting
multiple versions.

### Code analysis

There are a number of Terraform focused static analysis tools in use at
GDS. While none of them are yet ubiquitous they can help ensure your
code is more idiomatic, consistent and secure and you should consider the
benefits they could bring to your build pipelines.

 * [checkov][] - "detects security and compliance misconfigurations"

 * [tfsec][] - "spots potential security issues"

 * [tflint][] "linter focused on possible errors, best practices and so on."

## AWS Cloud Development Kit (CDK)

Some teams are using [CDK][] to configure AWS infrastructure. CDK allows you to define your 
cloud infrastructure using a familiar programming language. This can be useful when you need 
to use programmatic logic to define your infrastructure, or when you want to take advantage 
of type safety and IDE support.

### When to use CDK

Consider using CDK when:

* your infrastructure is designed to be 100% AWS Serverless resources 
* you build experimental infrastructure or prototypes that are not intended to be long lived
* your team have no existing Terraform expertise and no separate team who can help you manage infrastructure
* your team are predominantly or entirely developers who 
    * prefer using a programming language over declarative configuration.
    * only require high-level abstractions ([L2/L3 constructs][])

Consider using both CDK and Terraform if you have complex use cases where CDK handles application infrastructure and Terraform manages foundational or multi-cloud resources. 
This adds very significant complexity, so only go hybrid if you have specific reasons.

### Languages

CDK supports multiple programming languages including TypeScript, Python, Java, "C#" and Go. 
TypeScript and Python are the most commonly used languages for CDK at GDS, see section on 
[programming languages](/standards/programming-languages.html) for more information on our preferred 
languages.

### Code analysis

Each CDK supported language has its own set of analysis tools. Common tools that focus on CDK 
definitons that should be considered include:

 * [checkov][] - "detects security and compliance misconfigurations"

 * [cdk-nag][] - "AWS Native tooling for checking CDK code for best practices"

